DS Construction

Adjacent relationship: next, prev, inv
Incident relationship: origin, loop/face, edge

struct vertex {
  vec3d position;
  int halfedge;  //stores only 1 HE, the rest can be found by inv(next) like below
};
struct halfedge {
  int origin,ni,ti; (pointer-based trade off sequential access vs single access vs memory)
  int next,inv,li;
};
struct loop {
  int halfedge; //stores only 1 HE, the rest can be found by next
  bool is_border;
};
struct halfedge_mesh {
vector&lt;vertex&gt; vertices;
vector&lt;vec3d&gt; normals;
vector&lt;vec2d&gt; texCoords;
vector&lt;halfedge&gt; halfedges;
vector&lt;loop&gt; loops;
};

So, from an OBJ. file, what of these relationship can be directly inferred?

actually everything when reading the face: origin, next, loop BUT EXCEPT FOR inv, that neads to find what face adjacent to current face



Vertex Circulator:
int h0 = inv(vertexHalfEdge(vi)); //usually start with the inverse
int hi = h0;
do {
  useNeighbor(origin(hi));
  hi = inv(next(hi)); //always inv(next)
} while (hi != h0); //until back to beginning


Inverse Matching

Goal: finding the inv pointer for every halfedge in the mesh by placing them next to each other
Idea: Easy:

Sort internally v1 -&gt; v2 vs v2 -&gt; v1 in format smaller-&gt;bigger
Sort the indices along the smaller column
End effect:


HE exists twice are matched, they are internal
HE exists once are boundary
HE exists more than twice are non-manifold

This way we can extract Boundary Loop by for each unmatched HE, define all the inverse, and the inverse keep traversing next until it come back to the beginning

Euler Method

Explicit Euler Method: Energy increases \[
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{x}_{n+1} &= \mathbf{x}_n + h \cdot \mathbf{v}_n \\
\mathbf{v}_{n+1} &= \mathbf{v}_n + h \cdot \mathbf{a}_n
\end{aligned}
\]
Implicit Euler Method: Energy decreases. This is a linear system of equations 2 phương trình 2 ẩn, we can solve it analytically normally, no problem!!! \[
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{x}_{n+1} &= \mathbf{x}_n + h \cdot \mathbf{v}_{n+1} \\
\mathbf{v}_{n+1} &= \mathbf{v}_n + h \cdot \mathbf{a}_{n+1}
\end{aligned}
\]
Symplectic Euler Method (Euler Cromer): Energy conserved \[
\begin{aligned}
\mathbf{v}_{n+1} &= \mathbf{v}_n + h \cdot \mathbf{a}_n \\
\mathbf{x}_{n+1} &= \mathbf{x}_n + h \cdot \mathbf{v}_{n+1}
\end{aligned}
\]

But why sympletic Euler energy conserved? you calculate the new velocity first using the current acceleration, and then immediately use that new velocity to calculate the new position =&gt; avoid energy explosion.

Variance Problem
Return \(g_t^m\) rewards the action when it is positive, and punish the action when it is negative. But some cases all actions can be positive, just some are less positive than other =&gt; it should not be encouraged.
Solution: With baseline (e.g., \(V_\pi(s,w)\)) =&gt; then we have \[\mathbf{\theta} \leftarrow \mathbf{\theta} + \alpha \gamma^t (g_t^m - b(s_t^m)) \nabla_{\mathbf{\theta}} \ln \pi(a_t^m|s_t^m, \mathbf{\theta})\] so that:

if \(g_t^m &gt; V_\pi(s,w)\), the scaling factor is positive =&gt; increase probability of action \(a\)
if \(g_t^m &lt; V_\pi(s,w)\), the scaling factor is negative =&gt; decrease probability of action \(a\)

Sum up Kalman Filter Algorithm

Predict (Motion Update) We project our current state and uncertainty forward in time using the motion model. \[
\begin{aligned}
\check{\mathbf{x}}_k &= \mathbf{A}_k \hat{\mathbf{x}}_{k-1} + \mathbf{u}_k \\
\check{\mathbf{P}}_k &= \mathbf{A}_k \hat{\mathbf{P}}_{k-1} \mathbf{A}_k^T + \mathbf{R}
\end{aligned}
\]
Update (Measurement Update) First, we calculate the Kalman Gain (\(\mathbf{K}\)), which determines how much we trust the new sensor data versus our internal prediction: \[
\mathbf{K} = \check{\mathbf{P}}_k \mathbf{C}_k^T (\mathbf{C}_k \check{\mathbf{P}}_k \mathbf{C}_k^T + \mathbf{Q}_k)^{-1}
\] Then, we calculate the Posterior state and covariance: \[
\begin{aligned}
\hat{\mathbf{x}}_k &= \check{\mathbf{x}}_k + \mathbf{K}(\mathbf{z}_k - \mathbf{C}_k \check{\mathbf{x}}_k) \\
\hat{\mathbf{P}}_k &= (\mathbf{I} - \mathbf{K} \mathbf{C}_k) \check{\mathbf{P}}_k
\end{aligned}
\]
